  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is anabolic resistance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Anabolic resistance is the reduced ability of older muscle to respond to protein and produce new muscle tissue. After around age 40, the same protein dose that once triggered muscle protein synthesis becomes less effective — meaning you need more protein, delivered in larger per-meal doses, to get the same anabolic response."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much leucine do men over 40 need per meal to overcome anabolic resistance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Research suggests men over 40 need approximately 3.5–4g of leucine per meal to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis — compared to approximately 2–2.5g for younger adults. This higher leucine threshold is the primary reason older men need 30–40g of complete protein per meal rather than the 20–25g that younger men can get away with."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much protein per meal do men over 40 need because of anabolic resistance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most research points to 30–40 grams of protein per meal for men over 40 to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis. Smaller doses — say 15–20 grams — that worked fine in your 20s are often no longer enough to clear the anabolic threshold as you age."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why does anabolic resistance happen?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The exact mechanisms are still being studied, but the leading factors include reduced sensitivity to leucine (the amino acid that acts as the trigger for muscle protein synthesis), slower digestion and amino acid uptake, and declining hormonal signals like testosterone and IGF-1. The result is a higher protein dose required to get the same muscle-building signal."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is anabolic resistance the same as sarcopenia?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No — anabolic resistance is the mechanism, sarcopenia is the outcome. Anabolic resistance means muscle becomes less responsive to protein. When that blunted response goes unaddressed for years — combined with insufficient protein intake — the progressive muscle loss we call sarcopenia is what results."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you reverse anabolic resistance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You cannot fully reverse the biological changes of aging, but you can compensate for anabolic resistance effectively. The primary strategies are increasing total daily protein intake (targeting around 1.2 g/kg of body weight), ensuring each meal delivers a meaningful dose (30+ grams), prioritizing leucine-rich protein sources like whey, and combining protein intake with resistance training."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
