    <section class="faq-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is anabolic resistance?</h3>
          <p>Anabolic resistance is the reduced ability of older muscle to respond to protein and produce new muscle tissue. After around age 40, the same protein dose that once triggered muscle protein synthesis becomes less effective — meaning you need more protein, delivered in larger per-meal doses, to get the same anabolic response.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much leucine do men over 40 need per meal?</h3>
          <p>Research suggests approximately 3.5–4g of leucine per meal to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis in men over 40 — compared to 2–2.5g for younger adults. In practical terms this means 30–40g of complete protein per meal from high-quality sources. You don't need to track leucine directly — adequate complete protein grams per meal is the reliable proxy.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much protein per meal do men over 40 need because of anabolic resistance?</h3>
          <p>Most research points to 30–40 grams of protein per meal for men over 40 to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis. Smaller doses — say 15–20 grams — that worked fine in your 20s are often no longer enough to clear the anabolic threshold as you age.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why does anabolic resistance happen?</h3>
          <p>The leading factors include reduced sensitivity of the mTOR pathway to leucine (the amino acid that triggers muscle protein synthesis), slower digestion and amino acid uptake, and declining hormonal signals like testosterone and IGF-1. The result is a higher protein dose required to get the same muscle-building signal.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is anabolic resistance the same as sarcopenia?</h3>
          <p>No — anabolic resistance is the mechanism, sarcopenia is the outcome. Anabolic resistance means muscle becomes less responsive to protein. When that blunted response goes unaddressed for years — combined with insufficient protein intake — the progressive muscle loss we call sarcopenia is what results.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can you reverse anabolic resistance?</h3>
          <p>You cannot fully reverse the biological changes of aging, but you can compensate effectively. The primary strategies are increasing total daily protein (targeting around 1.2g/kg of body weight), ensuring each meal delivers 30–40g of complete protein to clear the leucine threshold, and combining protein intake with consistent resistance training.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

